<h2>Use Cases</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Brand color matching:</strong> Your client sends a logo. Pick the exact brand colors from it for use in your CSS or design tools.</li>
  <li><strong>Recreating designs:</strong> You see a color palette in a screenshot that you want to use in your project — pick each color and copy the hex codes.</li>
  <li><strong>Photography color grading:</strong> Sample the dominant color from a reference photo to match the mood in your design.</li>
  <li><strong>Accessibility checking:</strong> Pick a text color and a background color, then paste them into a contrast checker.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to Get a Color Code from a Website</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Press <kbd>F12</kbd> to open browser DevTools → Elements tab → hover over elements to see colors in the computed styles.</li>
  <li>Or: take a full-page screenshot (browser extension or OS screenshot), upload to the Image Color Picker, and click anywhere.</li>
</ol>

<h2>HEX vs RGB vs HSL — Which to Use?</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>HEX:</strong> Best for copy-pasting into HTML, CSS, and most design tools. Six-character format (#rrggbb).</li>
  <li><strong>RGB:</strong> Useful in CSS <code>rgb()</code> and <code>rgba()</code> functions. Clear representation of red, green, blue channel values (0–255).</li>
  <li><strong>HSL:</strong> Best for design intuition. Hue (0–360°), Saturation (0–100%), Lightness (0–100%). Easy to create lighter or darker versions by adjusting L.</li>
</ul>

